 {"id":"git_safety_guard-0fv0","title":"[Scan] Implement Dockerfile RUN command extractor","description":"# Task: Implement Dockerfile RUN command extractor

## Parent Epic: Scan Extractors (git_safety_guard-5rbb)

## Objective

Create an extractor that parses Dockerfiles and extracts shell commands from RUN instructions for security scanning.

## Dockerfile RUN Syntax

### Shell Form
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y nginx

### Exec Form  
RUN ["apt-get", "update"]

### Multi-line
RUN apt-get update \
    && apt-get install -y nginx \
    && apt-get clean

## Extraction Logic

1. Parse Dockerfile line by line
2. Identify RUN instructions (case-insensitive)
3. Handle line continuations (backslash at end)
4. Extract shell form as-is
5. Convert exec form to shell equivalent
6. Track line numbers for reporting

## Implementation

pub struct DockerfileExtractor;

impl CommandExtractor for DockerfileExtractor {
    fn name(&self) -> &str { "dockerfile" }

    fn file_patterns(&self) -> &[&str] { 
        &["Dockerfile", "Dockerfile.*", "*.dockerfile"] 
    }

    fn extract(&self, content: &str) -> Vec<ExtractedCommand> {
        let mut commands = Vec::new();
        let mut current_run: Option<StringBuilder> = None;
        let mut start_line = 0;

        for (line_num, line) in content.lines().enumerate() {
            if let Some(ref mut run) = current_run {
                // Continue multi-line RUN
                run.append(line.trim_end_matches('\\'));
                if !line.trim().ends_with('\\') {
                    // End of multi-line
                    commands.push(ExtractedCommand {
                        command: run.finish(),
                        line_start: start_line,
                        line_end: line_num,
                        context: "RUN".to_string(),
                    });
                    current_run = None;
                }
            } else if line.trim().to_uppercase().starts_with("RUN ") {
                // New RUN instruction
                let cmd_part = line.trim()[4..].trim();
                if cmd_part.ends_with('\\') {
                    current_run = Some(StringBuilder::from(cmd_part.trim_end_matches('\\')));
                    start_line = line_num;
                } else {
                    commands.push(ExtractedCommand {
                        command: parse_run_command(cmd_part),
                        line_start: line_num,
                        line_end: line_num,
                        context: "RUN".to_string(),
                    });
                }
            }
        }

        commands
    }
}

## Exec Form Handling

fn parse_run_command(cmd: &str) -> String {
    // Detect exec form: ["cmd", "arg1", "arg2"]
    if cmd.trim().starts_with('[') {
        // Parse JSON array and join with spaces
        if let Ok(parts) = serde_json::from_str::<Vec<String>>(cmd) {
            return parts.join(" ");
        }
    }
    // Shell form: return as-is
    cmd.to_string()
}

## Edge Cases

- Comments within RUN (shell comments #)
- Here-docs in RUN instructions
- ARG/ENV variable references
- Multi-stage builds (multiple FROMs)

## Test Cases

Test with real-world Dockerfiles:
- Simple single RUN
- Multi-line RUN with continuations
- Exec form RUN
- Mixed forms
- Build args in commands

## Acceptance Criteria

- Extracts all RUN commands from Dockerfiles
- Handles multi-line continuations
- Converts exec form to shell form
- Line numbers accurate for error reporting
- Graceful handling of malformed Dockerfiles

